Docker Container Security Hardening
Objectives
Design and deploy Docker containers that enforce least-privilege execution using non-root users, dropped Linux capabilities, and read-only filesystems
Implement mandatory access control on containers using AppArmor profiles to restrict unauthorized resource access
Construct a production-grade container security pipeline that combines image signing, runtime constraints, and resource limits into a single deployable configuration
Prerequisites
Comfort with Linux command-line operations including file permissions, user management, and process inspection
Familiarity with basic networking concepts such as ports, sockets, and TCP connections
Understanding of what a container is and how it differs from a virtual machine
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the Container Security Toolchain
Requirement 1
Install Docker Engine, AppArmor utilities, and Linux capability inspection tools on the bare Ubuntu instance. Docker Engine is the container runtime; AppArmor is a Linux kernel security module that enforces per-program access policies; capability tools allow you to inspect and manipulate the fine-grained privilege units that replace the all-or-nothing root model.

sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release
sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
Note: If the GPG URL above fails, consult the official Docker installation guide at https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/ for the current key URL.

sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list <<'EOF'
deb [arch=amd64 signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu jammy stable
EOF
Troubleshoot this step:

You may see "E: Malformed entry 1 in list file /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list" if the heredoc wrote extra whitespace or a literal backslash.
Inspect the file with cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list â it must be a single unbroken line; delete it with sudo rm /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list and recreate it.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io \
  apparmor apparmor-utils libcap2-bin python3 python3-pip
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
Troubleshoot this step:

You may see "E: Package 'docker-ce' has no installation candidate" if the sources list entry is malformed or the GPG key is missing.
Run apt-cache policy docker-ce â if the output shows no candidate, re-run the GPG import and sources list steps above, then sudo apt-get update -y.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
Requirement 2
Confirm every installed component is operational before proceeding. You must observe all four checks passing before moving to Task 2.

docker run --rm hello-world
sudo systemctl is-active apparmor
